docs.abstract: A total of 6,769 Defense Department personnel reported being sexually assaulted in the 2017 fiscal year. It was the largest yearly increase since 2014.
docs.snippet: A total of 6,769 Defense Department personnel reported being sexually assaulted in the 2017 fiscal year. It was the largest yearly increase since 2014.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — More than 6,700 Defense Department employees reported being sexually assaulted in the 2017 fiscal year — the highest number since the United States military began tracking reports more than a decade ago, according to Pentagon data released on Monday.

headline.main: Reports of Sexual Assault in the Military Rise by 10 Percent, Pentagon Finds
headline.print_headline: More Disclose Sex Assaults In the Military

docs.abstract: Interviews and newly obtained documents provide the Pentagon’s first public on-the-ground accounting of one of the bloodiest battles the military has faced in Syria since deploying to fight ISIS.
docs.snippet: Interviews and newly obtained documents provide the Pentagon’s first public on-the-ground accounting of one of the bloodiest battles the military has faced in Syria since deploying to fight ISIS.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The artillery barrage was so intense that the American commandos dived into foxholes for protection, emerging covered in flying dirt and debris to fire back at a column of tanks advancing under the heavy shelling. It was the opening salvo in a nearly four-hour assault in February by around 500 pro-Syrian government forces — including Russian mercenaries — that threatened to inflame already-simmering tensions between Washington and Moscow.

headline.main: How a 4-Hour Battle Between Russian Mercenaries and U.S. Commandos Unfolded in Syria
headline.print_headline: How U.S. Commandos Survived 4-Hour Battle  With Russians in Syria

docs.abstract: Democrats thought the weakness of a Supreme Court nominee would be health care and abortion. Then came Brett M. Kavanaugh’s writings on shielding presidents from investigation.
docs.snippet: Democrats thought the weakness of a Supreme Court nominee would be health care and abortion. Then came Brett M. Kavanaugh’s writings on shielding presidents from investigation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democrats who once saw health care and abortion as their best lines of attack against Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, President Trump’s Supreme Court nominee, are recalibrating their approach to go after him for his view that a sitting president should not have to answer questions in a criminal case, much less face indictment.

headline.main: Democrats Zero In on Kavanaugh’s Defense of Presidential Power
headline.print_headline: In Judge’s Views on Presidential Power, Democrats See a Line of Attack

docs.abstract: A group of bipartisan lawmakers emerged as the negotiators behind a potential deal to end the gridlock and reopen the government.
docs.snippet: A group of bipartisan lawmakers emerged as the negotiators behind a potential deal to end the gridlock and reopen the government.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On the second day of the shutdown, a bipartisan group of senators emerged as a primary force behind the effort to end the gridlock and reopen the government. More than 20 lawmakers, some facing challenging re-election bids, met behind closed doors and brokered a compromise that the Senate advanced 81 to 18 on Monday.

headline.main: Here Are the Senators Who Brokered a Bipartisan Solution to the Government Shutdown

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A lawsuit accusing President Trump of violating the Constitution by maintaining a financial interest in his company’s Washington hotel cleared a critical hurdle on Wednesday when a federal judge allowed the case to move forward.
